04763nam a22008295i 9780226485348DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017008989  a9780226485348  a(DE-B1597)521339  a(OCoLC)1013182893  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBH221.G3bA44 2017 4aBH221.G3bA44 2018 7aARC0000002bisacsh04a701.17223  aLH 611002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/94210:1 aAlexander, Zeynep Çelik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKinaesthetic Knowing :bAesthetics, Epistemology, Modern Design /cZeynep Çelik Alexander. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b10 color plates, 99 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: A Peculiar Experiment -- t1. Kinaesthetic Knowing: The Nineteenth- Century Biography of Another Kind of Knowledge -- t2. Looking: Wölfflin’s Comparative Vision -- t3. Affecting: Endell’s Mathematics of Living Feeling -- t4. Drawing: The Debschitz School and Formalism’s Subject -- t5. Designing: Discipline and Introspection at the Bauhaus -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs all knowledge the product of thought? Or can the physical interactions of the body with the world produce reliable knowledge? In late-nineteenth-century Europe, scientists, artists, and other intellectuals theorized the latter as a new way of knowing, which Zeynep Çelik Alexander here dubs “kinaesthetic knowing.” In this book, Alexander offers the first major intellectual history of kinaesthetic knowing and its influence on the formation of modern art and architecture and especially modern design education. Focusing in particular on Germany and tracing the story up to the start of World War II, Alexander reveals the tension between intellectual meditation and immediate experience to be at the heart of the modern discourse of aesthetics, playing a major part in the artistic and teaching practices of numerous key figures of the period, including Heinrich Wölfflin, Hermann Obrist, August Endell, László Moholy-Nagy, and many others. Ultimately, she shows, kinaesthetic knowing did not become the foundation of the human sciences, as some of its advocates had hoped, but it did lay the groundwork—at such institutions as the Bauhaus—for modern art and architecture in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAestheticsxPhysiological aspects. 0aAestheticsxPsychological aspects. 0aAesthetics, Germany19th century. 0aAesthetics, Germany20th century. 0aAesthetics, German-19th century. 0aAesthetics, German-20th century. 0aAesthetics-Physiological aspects. 0aAesthetics-Psychological aspects. 0aAesthetics. 0aArtxStudy and teachingzGermany. 0aArt-Study and teaching-Germany. 0aDesignxPhilosophy. 0aDesign-Philosophy. 0aKnowledge, Theory of. 0aPsychology and artzGermany. 0aPsychology and art-Germany. 0aPsychophysics. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh  aImperial Germany.  aaesthetics.  aepistemology.  aexperimental psychology.  aformalism.  akinaesthesia.  akinesthesia.  amodern design education.  amodernism.  apedagogy.  atechnique.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226485348423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226485348/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles